      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two distinct load configurations evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 static compression-bending configuration only. No additional load angles or load levels were evaluated. This limits the achieved level to 2, one below the required level of 3. This gap is noted as an open risk item; the sponsor committed to supplemental testing in the post-market surveillance plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA inputs match measured specimen properties and test-fixture geometry to within stated tolerances; no surrogate material substitutions.",
      "rationale": "CMM-measured screw and rod dimensions were used directly as FEA geometry inputs. Material properties from coupon tests on the same lot were assigned without surrogate substitution. Fixture stiffness was characterized experimentally and incorporated as a boundary condition spring. Input equivalency is therefore at the highest achievable level for this study design."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all three QoIs; statistical uncertainty in experimental mean propagated via t-distribution.",
      "rationale": "For all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm), E/uval ranged from 0.41 to 1.12 and percent differences ranged from 2.3% to 7.8%. Both acceptance criteria were satisfied. Experimental uncertainty was estimated from the N=11 sample using a t-distribution at 95% confidence."
    },
    {
